<DOC><DOCNO> AP880919-0269 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-19-88 1407EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-Immigrants-Poll 1stLd-Writethru   09-19 0241</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Immigrants-Poll, 1st Ld-Writethru,0248</SECOND><HEAD>Majority of Americans View Immigrants As Negative Impact OnEconomy</HEAD><NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 5-6 bgng `Nineteen percent ...' to ADD thatremainder had no clear opinion.</NOTE><DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A majority of Americans believe immigrantshave a negative impact on the economy, and almost half said thenewcomers contribute little to American culture, according to apoll published today.   ``A lot of our old prejudices are still at work,'' said MauriceA. Roberts, editor of Interpreter Releases, a Washington-basednational immigration journal, said of the Los Angeles Times poll.   The poll surveyed 1,418 people nationwide last weekend, fourmonths after the one-year immigrant legalization program ended andtwo months after the government began full enforcement of sanctionsagainst employers who hire illegal aliens.   Asked whether immigrants get more or less from the U.S economythrough social services and unemployment benefits than theycontribute through taxes and work, 64 percent of the respondentssaid immigrants take more than they give.   Nineteen percent said immigrants contributed more, while 4percent said immigrants benefited and contributed equally to theeconomy. The rest of the respondents had no clear opinion,according to the poll.   Asked whether immigrants have made a contribution in the lastdecade to American culture, 46 percent said they haven't, while 40percent said immigrants have enriched the culture. The rest had noclear opinion.   The margin of error was four percentage points in eitherdirection.</TEXT></DOC>